Author::::Daniels78
DateTime::::2016-03-04T17:40:51Z
Sea level is widely tracked by the IPCC as having an estimated height increase of about a meter by 2100. Many reports however do not include a progressive upward trend in the rate of increase, due to such various things as darkening of ice sheet during melt, lubrication between bedrock & water after melting and other reasons I can't remember. All in all, this (as with many IPCC figures) is highly conservative so as not to be panic-inducing. James Hansen of NASA (whom many will have heard of) recently put this figure to about 5 meters, although his estimate is either 50, 100 or 200 years in the future. A peer-reviewed (or in the process of being peer-reviewed) article written with 16 other scientists is published online. What many now think is that given the IPCCs notorious conservatism, and Mr Hansen's 30 year proven track record on climate change, the figure will be closer to 2 meters.



